div1.p: IN THE CIRCUIT COURT OF THE UNITED STATES FOR THE NINTH CIRCUIT WESTERN DISTRICT OF WASHINGTON
IN THE MATTER OF THE APPLICATION OF L.J. URANN FOR A WRIT OF HABEAS CORPUS.} TRAVERSE.
And now comes L.J. Urann, by his attorney Vince H. Fabern and for traverse of the return herein alleges as follows.
I.
Said petitioner denies that his detention is lawful but on the contrary that it is unlawful, forceable and against his will.
II.

That said Governor's warrant was issued contrary to law and against the provisions of the constitution and sections 5270 and 5280 inclusive and contrary to the law and the statute in the State of Massachusettes.
III.

That it is not true that the petitioner is a fugitive from justice or that larceny is a felony or a treason or other similar crime under that law of the State of Massachusetts and that said petitioner has not violated any law of the State of Massachusetts which is the subject of extradition between the States of the United States.
IV.

That the petitioner in the month of January, 1904, became indebted to the complaining witness in the State of Massachusetts upon an account for money had and received and that the amount thereof was adjusted and agreed upon in the month of April, 1904,
and that said amount of money was stipulated and agreed between the parties.
V.

That thereafter it was agreed between the complaining witness and the petitioner that said sum of money should be paid partly in cash and partly in security and in persuance thereof the said complaining witness went to the State of Main and inspected the security consisting of a farm of the agreed value of Five Thousand Dollars ($5,000.00) and the balance amounting to Three Thousand Dollars ($3,000.00) was in cash and that said sum was determined upon between the parties after full knowledge of all the facts in the premises were known.
VI.

That the complaining witness and petitioner lived near neighbors in Boston and that the petitioner stayed in Boston assisting in said adjustment for about five months and that for many months prior to the time that the petitioner left the State of Massachusetts the complaining witness knew that the petitioner was going to leave the State and that he intended to go to Seattle, State of Washington to reside and said complaining witness knew at all times the address and residence and place of business of the petitioner for more than one year last past.
VII.

That after the complaining witness knew of the facts more than five (5) circuitseparate sessions of different grand juries were had and held in the presinct where said parties resided and the complaining witness made no claims of criminal intent and since this petitioner has resided in the State of Washington more than eleven (11) sessions of the Grand Jury were held in said presinct
and no charge of crime was made.
VIII.

That the prosecution or pretended prosecution is not made in good faith nor for the purpose of punishment of crime or any other public purpose but only the purpose of collection and extorrion and for private game.
WHEREFORE your petitioner prays for relief as he has heretofor set forth in his petition for the writ and that he be discharged and released.
Vince H. Faben
Attorney for Petitioner.
State of Washington County of King} ss
L.J. Urann being first duly sworn on oath deposes and says: That he is the petitioner; that he has read the foregoing traverse and knows the contents thereof and believes the same to be true.
Louis J. Urann
Subscribed and sworn to before me this 3rd day of July, 1905.
Vince H. Faben
Notary Public in and for the State of Washington, residing at Seattle.
